1 Introduction

1.1 Markdown

Markdown is a lightweight markup language with plain text formatting syntax (Easy-to-read, easy-to-write plain text format). It is designed so that it can be converted to HTML and many other formats (e.g.Â PDF, MS Word).

It saves and executes code in order to generate fully reproducible reports in dozens of static and dynamic output formats.

Like other markup languages (e.g.Â HTML and Latex), it is completely independent from R.

1.2 R Markdown

â¢ R Markdown is an extension of the markdown syntax. R Markdown files are plain text files that typically have the file extension .Rmd. They are written using an extension of markdown syntax that enables R code to be embedded in them in a way which can later be executed.

â¢ The R package rmarkdown package feeds the .Rmd file to knitr, which executes all of the code chunks and creates a new markdown (.md) document which includes the code and itâs output.

â¢ It is subsequently tranformed into html/.tex/.docx by pandoc. .tex files need to be transformed by pdflatex into .pdf files.

â¢ rmardown, knitr, and `pandoc are built in Rstudio. pdflatex is not. Weâll come back to that later. (https://yihui.name/tinytex/)

â¢ When you click the Knit button a document will be generated that includes both content as well as the output of any embedded R code chunks within the document.

3 Metadata (YAML Ainât Markup Language )

---
title: "Rmarkdown"
author: "Sebastien Renaut"
date: '2018-03-12'
output: html_document
---

â¢ Why YAML (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/YAML#History_and_name) ?

â¢ It uses Python-style indentation to specify general options and what kind of document will be created.

â¢ It is not required (defaults then apply)

â¢ Many options possible depending what type of document you are generating. See below for some examples.

â¢ Note that several options can be specified either for the whole document (in the YAML header), or the code chunks, or both (chunks options superseede YAML header).

3.1 Customizing metadata

---
title: "Rmarkdown"
author: "Sebastien Renaut"
date: "September 07, 2018"
output:
html_document:
highlight: tango
number_sections: T
theme: united toc: yes
toc_depth: 3
---

3.3 Table of content options

â¢ toc: yes Generate TOC â¢ toc_depth:3 depth of TOC
â¢ number_sections:T Add section numbering to headers (e.g., number_sections: true).

3.4 theme, highlight, tabs, other options

â¢ theme: specifies the theme to use for the page (âceruleanâ, âjournalâ, âflatlyâ, âreadableâ, âspacelabâ, âunitedâ, and âcosmoâ) â¢ highlight = Syntax highlighting style (e.g. âtangoâ, âpygmentsâ, âkateâ, âzenburnâ) â¢ include If FALSE, knitr will run the chunk but not include the chunk in the final document

4 Code chunks

Code Chunk output can be customized with knitr options, arguments set in the {} of a chunk header. Below, I use five arguments: â¢ In this example, the first code chunk specifies global options. These can be redefined later.
â¢ include = FALSE prevents code and results from appearing in the finished file. R Markdown still runs the code in the chunk, and the results can be used by other chunks.
â¢ echo = FALSE prevents code, but not the results from appearing in the finished file. This is a useful way to embed figures. â¢ message = FALSE prevents messages that are generated by code from appearing in the finished file.
â¢ warning = FALSE prevents warnings that are generated by code from appearing in the finished.
â¢ fig.cap = "..." adds a caption to graphical results.
â¢ fig.width=..., fig.height=... to change figure width/heigth.
â¢ see cheat sheet for more info.

#This is an example using include = T, message = T, warning=T, echo = T, fig.cap="Figure 1".
x = rexp(1000)
min(x)
## [1] 0.0002902467
max(x)
## [1] 5.536743
plot(x)

Figure 1

â¢ In this example, the first code chunk specifies global options. These can be redefined later.

bash

ls -thor

## drwxr-xr-x  3 jerry    96B  7 Sep 10:53 rmarkdown_main_files

python

x = "hello python"
print(x.split(' '))
## ['hello', 'python']

perl

print "Hello World!";
## Hello World!

5.2 References, footnotes, bibliography

â¢ Footnotes are easy when you have a few references1
â¢ Otherwise, you may specify a bibliography in the YAML metadata header. Example (Cornwell et al., 2016).

...
csl: csl/peerj.csl
bibliography: biblio/test_library.bib
---

â¢ csl specifies the reference format. Here I just googled and download the .csl file for PlosOne. Most journals should be on this github repo. But you could create your own (YACL - Yet Another Citation Languageâ¦)

â¢ bib is my reference library for this project. Here: a .bib file I created in [Papers3 (reference management software) (https://www.readcube.com/papers/mac) with some references (eg. Yoshida et al. (2014), Thibert-Plante & Hendry (2010), Wagner et al. (2012)).

5.4 Including Tables

â¢ By default, R Markdown displays data frames and matrixes as they would be in the R terminal (in a monospaced font). It is not very pretty.
â¢ If you prefer that data be displayed with additional formatting you can use the knitr::kable function, as in the .Rmd file below.

#default R printout
print(head(mtcars))
##                    mpg cyl disp  hp drat    wt  qsec vs am gear carb

## Datsun 710        22.8   4  108  93 3.85 2.320 18.61  1  1    4    1
## Hornet 4 Drive    21.4   6  258 110 3.08 3.215 19.44  1  0    3    1
## Hornet Sportabout 18.7   8  360 175 3.15 3.440 17.02  0  0    3    2
## Valiant           18.1   6  225 105 2.76 3.460 20.22  1  0    3    1
#kable (from knitr)
library(knitr)
kable(head(mtcars),digits =1,caption = "An motorcars table")
